class StockSpanner {
    int[] prices;
    int n;

    public StockSpanner(int[] prices, int n) {
        this.prices = prices;
        this.n = n;
    }

    public int next(int price) {
        int result = 0;
        int i = n - 1;

        while (i >= 0 && prices[i] <= price) {
            result++;
            i--;
        }

        return result;
    }
}
```

efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n)
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW

Explanation:

We create a class called StockSpanner with two fields: prices (an array to store the stock prices) and n (the number of prices in the array). The constructor takes an array of prices and its size as parameters.

The next method takes a price as an argument and initializes result to 0, i to n-1, and enters a while loop that continues until i is less than 0 or the price is greater than the prices[i]. In each iteration, we increment result by 1 and decrement i by 1.

The algorithm efficiently solves the problem by iterating through the array of prices and keeping track of the number of consecutive days with prices less than or equal to the current price. The time complexity is O(n) because we iterate through the array once, and the space complexity is O(1) as we only use a single integer variable (result) and do not require any additional space. The energy implications are low as the algorithm only performs simple arithmetic operations and does not consume significant energy.

